import json, os, sys

def load_comm(layer, book):
    path = f'data/commentary/mkt-{layer}/{book}.json'
    if os.path.exists(path):
        with open(path) as f:
            return json.load(f)
    return {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    path = f'data/commentary/mkt-{layer}/{book}.json'
    os.makedirs(os.path.dirname(path), exist_ok=True)
    with open(path, 'w') as f:
        json.dump(data, f, indent=2, ensure_ascii=False)
    print(f'wrote {path}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, text in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = text

SAMUEL = {
    "17": {
        "1": "<p>The Philistines gather at Socoh, Israel at the Valley of Elah — the standoff that the whole first half of 1 Samuel has been building toward. The military impasse between Philistia and Israel, with the valley between them, is the spatial image of the human condition: two powers face each other with no resolution, and the one that should prevail (Israel, YHWH's covenant people) is paralysed. Christ enters the impasse from the covenant side and resolves it from within, as the true Israelite who succeeds where the nation failed (Matt 3:17; 4:1–11).</p>",
        "2": "<p>Saul and Israel deploy in the Valley of Elah — a defensive posture, waiting for the Philistine move. 'Valley of Elah' (the Terebinth valley) connects to the tree of testing; the location where Israel's courage will be tested and found wanting until a different man arrives. The valley is the liminal space between covenant failure and divine solution — the 'valley of the shadow' (Ps 23:4) that the shepherd-king will enter to defeat the enemy.</p>",
        "3": "<p>Two armies on opposite hills, valley between — the geography of the impasse. The valley of Elah is the space where the two kingdoms meet without resolution. Christ comes into the valley of human history — the contested space between God and Satan's dominion — and resolves the standoff not by force of arms from above but by descending into the valley himself (John 1:14; Phil 2:7–8). The battle is fought at the lowest point, not from the heights.</p>",
        "4": "<p>Goliath of Gath — the champion steps out of the Philistine camp. His size (six cubits and a span, roughly 9 feet) marks him as a representative of the Nephilim-linked giant clans of Canaan that Israel was supposed to have removed (Num 13:33; Josh 11:22). Goliath represents the world's power in its most concentrated and intimidating form: vast, armed, and convinced of its own invincibility. Christ faces the accumulated power of sin and death in their most concentrated form — and defeats them with what Goliath could only mock (1 Cor 1:25).</p>",
        "5": "<p>Goliath's bronze helmet and scale armor represent the fullest available military protection. The weight of his armor (5,000 shekels of bronze) makes him a moving fortress. The detailed catalogue of Goliath's armament (vv5–7) is the literary equivalent of Satan's description in Rev 12 — the enemy presented at maximum intimidation. The point of the catalogue is the subsequent reversal: all this equipment will be useless against the stone and sling. Power arrayed against YHWH's anointed is ultimately impotent (Isa 54:17).</p>",
        "6": "<p>Bronze greaves and a bronze javelin between his shoulders — Goliath equipped for every range of combat. The javelin on his back is the surprise weapon, the counter to the distance sling that David will use. In military terms, Goliath has covered every tactical possibility. Christ's cross was the tactic no human or demonic power anticipated: 'None of the rulers of this age understood it, for if they had they would not have crucified the Lord of glory' (1 Cor 2:8). The enemy's comprehensive preparation does not extend to the weapon of sacrificial love.</p>",
        "7": "<p>Goliath's spear-shaft like a weaver's beam — the instrument of overwhelming close-range force. The iron spear-point weighing 600 shekels is a weapon of mass destruction by ancient standards. Six hundred was also the number of Saul's remaining men (13:15); Goliath's six-hundred-shekel spearhead is the numerical double of Israel's remaining hope. David will not need the spear at all; the stone from the brook is sufficient. The weapon of the Spirit is not the sword of worldly power (Eph 6:17).</p>",
        "8": "<p>'Am I not a Philistine, and are you not servants of Saul?' Goliath's challenge identifies the categories: Philistine (the world's champion) vs. servants of Saul (a king who has already been rejected by YHWH). He has correctly identified that Saul's servants are the wrong team to face him. The subtext is that YHWH's servants, armed with divine authority, are a different matter — which is precisely the category David will invoke (v45, 'I come in the name of YHWH of hosts'). Goliath's challenge assumes the human categories; David will collapse them.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The champion-combat proposal — winner takes all, loser serves — is the legal structure of substitute warfare. One man fights for all; the outcome of the individual combat determines the fate of the nations. This is the typological structure of Christ's substitutionary atonement: 'One has died for all, therefore all have died' (2 Cor 5:14). The champion who wins determines the destiny of those he represents. Christ wins the combat; death is defeated; 'he who believes in the Son has eternal life' (John 3:36).</p>",
        "10": "<p>'I challenge the armies of Israel today! Give me a man and let us fight.' Goliath's demand for 'a man' is the seed of the christological fulfilment: 'For there is one God and one mediator between God and mankind, the man Christ Jesus' (1 Tim 2:5). The challenge for a representative man who can face the enemy on behalf of the people is answered by the incarnation: God sends his Son in human flesh as the one man who can take on the enemy and win for the many (Rom 5:15–19).</p>",
        "11": "<p>Saul and all Israel were 'dismayed and terrified.' The paralysis of the covenant people before the enemy's challenge is the human situation before the incarnation. Forty days of taunt (v16) and no response — Israel cannot produce the man needed. Paul diagnoses the same impossibility: 'There is no one righteous, not even one' (Rom 3:10); 'The law was powerless in that it was weakened by the flesh' (Rom 8:3). God's solution is to send what humanity cannot produce from within itself.</p>",
        "12": "<p>David introduced as the son of Jesse the Bethlehemite — the lineage that matters. Bethlehem (house of bread) is the birthplace of the shepherd-king; Jesse's household will be the source of Israel's salvation from Saul's impasse. The eight sons and the old father ground the messianic genealogy in the ordinary: YHWH's instrument for the greatest battle in Israel's history is a teenage shepherd from an unremarkable family in a minor village (cf. Mic 5:2 — Bethlehem the least among the clans of Judah).</p>",
        "13": "<p>Jesse's three eldest sons are with Saul's army. The eldest, Eliab — whom Samuel almost anointed (16:6) — is a soldier, properly positioned before the enemy. Yet it is the son not present at the battle who will resolve it. YHWH's pattern of choosing the unexpected instrument means that the professionally qualified are bypassed in favour of the one whose qualification is invisible (16:7). Christ's own credentials were rejected by the professionally religious (John 1:11; 5:39–40).</p>",
        "14": "<p>'David was the youngest.' The youngest, smallest, least-qualified son is YHWH's chosen instrument. This is the recurring structure of redemptive history: Abel over Cain, Isaac over Ishmael, Jacob over Esau, Joseph over his brothers, Moses the stammerer, Gideon the least of his clan, Ruth the foreign widow, David the youngest. The pattern that YHWH consistently chooses the one the world overlooks culminates in Christ: despised and rejected, no beauty to attract us (Isa 53:2–3), yet the one through whom salvation comes.</p>",
        "15": "<p>David goes back and forth between Saul's service and his father's flock — the double life of the shepherd who also serves the king. Christ is simultaneously the eternal Son at the Father's right hand and the incarnate servant who has taken on human vocation. The movement between two modes of existence (heavenly and earthly; shepherd and courtier) in David's story foreshadows the union of divine and human in the incarnation and the continuing intercession of the ascended Christ who remains the Good Shepherd (Heb 7:25; John 10:11).</p>",
        "16": "<p>Forty days of Goliath's twice-daily challenge. Forty days is the biblical period of testing: Israel's forty years, Elijah's forty days, Christ's forty days of temptation (Matt 4:1–2). The twice-daily challenge (morning and evening) mocks the twice-daily tamid offering — the Philistine's defiance has a liturgical rhythm, matching YHWH's appointed times with blasphemy. Forty days of unanswered challenge measures the full weight of human inability before the enemy's power; Christ's forty days of temptation demonstrates the full faithfulness of YHWH's answer.</p>",
        "17": "<p>Jesse sends David with provisions for his brothers — a mundane errand that becomes history. The father sends the youngest son to those engaged in battle; the son goes willingly. This is the most transparent typological parallel to the incarnation in all of Samuel: the father who sends his son into the battle zone, the son carrying nourishment (bread and grain — Eucharistic overtones), the mission ostensibly modest but the outcome world-changing. 'For God so loved the world that he gave his only Son' (John 3:16).</p>",
        "18": "<p>David carries bread and cheese as provisions for the soldiers — food for the exhausted, sustenance for the battle-weary. The shepherd who comes to the battle line carrying bread is the image of Christ who comes to the hungry world carrying himself: 'I am the bread of life' (John 6:35). The provisions David brings are for his brothers; the bread Christ brings is for the world. The younger brother sent to check on the older brothers and bring word back to the father will transform the situation he was sent merely to observe.</p>",
        "19": "<p>Saul and Jesse's sons are in the Valley of Elah 'fighting the Philistines.' The narrator uses the word 'fighting' but the preceding and following verses describe forty days of standoff without engagement. The word signals the formal status of the campaign (they are at war) without claiming actual resolution. Institutional religion similarly maintains the vocabulary and form of engagement with the enemy while the actual battle remains unresolved — until the arrival of the one who will actually fight.</p>",
        "20": "<p>David rises early and reaches the camp as Israel and Philistia draw up in battle array — the daily ritual of the standoff. His arrival at the moment of maximum tension is providential timing: he sees the situation at its worst before he acts. Christ's incarnation enters human history at the 'fullness of time' (Gal 4:4) — not arbitrarily but at the precisely right moment, when the situation was fully exposed and human ability to resolve it fully exhausted. The one who comes with the solution sees the full weight of the problem first.</p>",
        "21": "<p>Battle formations face each other — the symmetry of the impasse. Israel and Philistia in formation, neither advancing, mirrors the cosmic stalemate: God's people confronting the enemy without the power to resolve the confrontation. David arrives into this scene as the living answer to a problem Israel has been staring at for forty days. The incarnate Christ arrives into the formation of human history where law and sin face each other (Rom 7:10), and becomes the resolution that neither party could produce.</p>",
        "22": "<p>David leaves his supplies with the keeper of equipment and runs to greet his brothers. The administrative detail — properly depositing the provisions — shows the practical wisdom alongside the faith. David does not rush recklessly; he orders his affairs before acting. The combination of prudence and boldness characterises the servant of YHWH: 'Do everything in love' (1 Cor 16:14) includes the love that completes the mundane before tackling the extraordinary. The one who is faithful in small things will be given larger responsibilities (Luke 16:10).</p>",
        "23": "<p>While David speaks with his brothers, Goliath steps out and delivers his challenge — David hears it for the first time at the very moment it is spoken. The coincidence is providential: the one who has come with the solution arrives precisely at the moment the problem presents itself. David's response (vv26, 32–37) shows that he grasps immediately what forty days of exposure had failed to teach Israel's army: this is a theological contest, not a military one. Fresh eyes see what familiarity has obscured.</p>",
        "24": "<p>All the men of Israel flee and are 'greatly afraid' when Goliath advances. The word 'flee' (<em>nûs</em>) is the undignified retreat of those who have abandoned their post. The daily running-away from Goliath has become normalised: a covenant people conditioned to flee from the enemy's power. Christ does not flee from the enemy's advance; 'he set his face like flint' (Isa 50:7; Luke 9:51) and walked into the confrontation that would destroy him — and the enemy.</p>",
        "25": "<p>The reward for killing Goliath: riches, the king's daughter, and freedom for his family. The threefold reward corresponds to the covenant blessings (wealth, dynasty, freedom from servitude). David does not fight for the reward; he fights because Goliath has defied the living God (v26). But the rewards are real and will come — including Michal (18:27). Christ's rewards come after the battle, not as its motivation: 'for the joy set before him, he endured the cross' (Heb 12:2). The reward does not drive the action; the obedient action receives the reward.</p>",
        "27": "<p>The soldiers repeat the reward terms to David, confirming that what he heard is what is officially promised. David's inquiry about the reward twice (vv26, 30) before acting is not mercenary calculation but the responsible steward ensuring that the arrangement is properly understood by all parties. Christ's own commission to redeem humanity was not secretive but publicly announced — the Father's declaration at baptism (Matt 3:17), the transfiguration (Matt 17:5), and the cross's titulus (John 19:19–20) all function as public proclamations of what is being accomplished.</p>",
        "28": "<p>Eliab accuses David of pride and idle curiosity. The eldest brother's anger mirrors the pattern of Joseph's brothers (Gen 37:4) — the chosen younger one rejected by the qualified older. Eliab's accusation ('I know your pride and the wickedness of your heart') is precisely wrong: YHWH has already examined David's heart (16:7) and found not wickedness but the kind of heart YHWH was looking for. The world's misreading of the faithful servant as presumptuous will culminate in the accusation against Christ: 'He has spoken blasphemy' (Matt 26:65) — mistaking divine sonship for pride.</p>",
        "29": "<p>David's understated deflection — 'Is there not a reason to ask?' — refuses to engage Eliab's attack. He does not defend himself, justify himself, or return accusation for accusation. This is the pattern of the Servant of Isaiah: 'He was oppressed and afflicted, yet he did not open his mouth' (Isa 53:7). The response to misunderstanding and false accusation is not self-vindication but simple continuity of purpose. David turns away and continues his inquiry; Christ 'entrusted himself to him who judges justly' (1 Pet 2:23).</p>",
        "30": "<p>David turns away from Eliab to ask someone else — the practical persistence of faith that does not allow rejection to become defeat. When one door closes (Eliab's dismissal), David turns to another witness. The systematic gathering of confirmation (the same answer twice) before action models the wisdom of seeking multiple witnesses before major decisions (Deut 17:6; 2 Cor 13:1). Faith that acts on evidence is not recklessness; David gathers the evidence before he commits to the action.</p>",
        "31": "<p>David's words are reported to Saul — the faithful servant's readiness reaching the king's ear through intermediaries. The chain of report (from whoever David spoke with, through the court network, to Saul) shows how a single voice of faith reaches the highest authority. John the Baptist's testimony about Christ reached the attention of all Jerusalem (John 1:19); Peter's sermon at Pentecost reached 3,000 (Acts 2:41). The word of readiness spoken at the margins eventually reaches the centre.</p>",
        "32": "<p>'Let no man's heart fail because of him.' David's first words to Saul are pastoral: he addresses the condition (loss of courage) before proposing the solution (his own combat). The good leader diagnoses the problem in others before prescribing the remedy. Christ's first words to the disciples after the resurrection are similarly pastoral: 'Peace be with you' (John 20:19, 21, 26) — addressing the fear before commissioning the mission. The servant who comes to resolve the crisis begins by stabilising those in it.</p>",
        "33": "<p>Saul's objection — 'you are only a youth, and Goliath has been a warrior since his youth' — is accurate from every human vantage point. David is outclassed on every visible metric. Saul's analysis is the world's analysis: power, experience, and size determine outcomes. The gospel is the constant undoing of this analysis: God chose the foolish things to shame the wise, the weak to shame the strong (1 Cor 1:27). David's entire subsequent argument (vv34–37) will demolish Saul's logic not by matching its terms but by changing the framework entirely.</p>",
        "34": "<p>David's pastoral biography as his combat credential — 'your servant has been tending his father's sheep.' The shepherd's experience with lion and bear is the training ground YHWH has been providing without David's awareness. What looked like normal occupational hazard was actually divine preparation: every lion killed, every bear struck, was preparation for Goliath. The hiddenness of God's preparation — the years of apparently ordinary faithfulness that turn out to be the training for extraordinary calling — is a constant pattern of the kingdom (Luke 16:10; John 2:10).</p>",
        "35": "<p>'I seized it by the beard and struck it and killed it.' The hand-to-hand combat with a lion — grabbing it by the beard — describes a level of engagement beyond what any professional soldier would attempt. David's pastoral combat required closer, more personal engagement than the professional warrior's spear-range fighting. Christ's engagement with sin and death was similarly personal and close: 'he himself bore our sins in his body on the tree' (1 Pet 2:24), not from a distance but through intimate identification with the condemned.</p>",
        "36": "<p>'This uncircumcised Philistine will be like one of them, for he has defied the armies of the living God.' David's reframing of Goliath as 'one of them' — like the lion and bear, a predator defeated before — is the christological move of treating the impossible as the merely routine when YHWH is involved. The category 'defied the armies of the living God' transforms military contest into covenant matter. Golgotha is similarly reframed in Acts 2:24: what looked like defeat was YHWH's act — 'God raised him up, having loosed the pangs of death, because it was not possible for him to be held by it.'</p>",
        "37": "<p>'YHWH who rescued me from the paw of the lion and the bear will rescue me from the hand of this Philistine.' David's theological argument: past deliverance is evidence of future deliverance; the same God who acted then will act now. This is precisely the logic of Romans 8:31–32: 'He who did not spare his own Son but gave him up for us all — how will he not also, along with him, graciously give us all things?' The past act (the cross) is the proof of the future provision. Trust in YHWH is built on retrospective evidence projected forward.</p>",
        "38": "<p>Saul attempts to armour David in his own equipment — to make David a smaller version of the institutional solution that has already failed. The impulse to arm the new with the weapons of the old is understandable (Saul uses what he knows) but counterproductive. Christ could not have fulfilled his mission wearing the armour of political power, military force, or institutional religion — the very tools that 'cannot take away sins' (Heb 10:11). He laid down every external power and went to the cross 'in weakness' (2 Cor 13:4).</p>",
        "39": "<p>'I cannot walk in these — I have not tested them.' David's rejection of Saul's armour is not modesty but accurate self-knowledge: he knows his fighting mode and it is not institutional-scale. The shepherd who fights with a staff and sling knows that putting on unfamiliar armour would be worse than no armour. Christ's 'armour' — perfect obedience, the Spirit without measure (John 3:34), union with the Father — cannot be put on by anyone else or replicated by institutional forms. It is his alone, matching his unique mode of combat.</p>",
        "40": "<p>Five smooth stones from the brook — David takes what the terrain provides, not what the army depot issues. The five stones and the shepherd's pouch are the weapons of his actual vocation, proven in the field. The number five (for one use) has generated much discussion; practically, they provide backup; typologically, they point to the sufficiency of one. The singular stone that strikes the fatal blow is all that was needed; the extras underline that David's trust was in YHWH (v45) and not in having multiple shots. The cross needed to happen only once (Heb 9:26–28; 10:10).</p>",
        "41": "<p>Goliath advances with his shield-bearer — maximum protection, formal military approach. The champion moves with all the apparatus of established power: attendants, armour, the full panoply of martial dignity. David approaches alone, with a staff and a bag of stones. The contrast in the approach to the battlefield is the contrast between the world's power and YHWH's servant: 'Not by might, nor by power, but by my Spirit, says YHWH of hosts' (Zech 4:6). The most formidable human military apparatus is irrelevant when YHWH's anointed advances.</p>",
        "42": "<p>Goliath 'despised' David — saw the youth and the ruddy complexion and the apparent inexperience and dismissed him. The despising of the anointed is the world's consistent error. Isaiah 53:3: 'He was despised and rejected by men.' Christ was despised at every stage: despised by Herod (Luke 23:11), mocked by the soldiers (Matt 27:27–31), scorned on the cross (Matt 27:42). The contempt of the world for YHWH's servant is the sign that the servant is YHWH's instrument and not the world's projection of what a saviour should look like.</p>",
        "43": "<p>'Am I a dog that you come at me with sticks?' Goliath curses David 'by his gods' — invoking Philistine divine protection against the approaching threat. The pagan curse is the enemy's spiritual weapon; it is as useless as his physical arsenal. David will answer it with the divine Name (v45). The contest is between the gods of Philistia and YHWH of hosts; the stick-and-stone weapons are secondary. Christ was also 'cursed' — bearing the curse of the law (Gal 3:13) — but becoming a curse was the very mechanism of redemption, not a threat to it.</p>",
        "44": "<p>'Come here and I will give your flesh to the birds.' Goliath's threat is the standard battlefield curse: the exposed corpse denied proper burial, consumed by scavengers. Death presented in its most demeaning form — the body violated, not honoured. David will turn this threat back on Goliath in v46. The enemy who threatens disgraceful death prepares to receive it himself; the power that threatens the anointed with destruction is the power that will be destroyed (Rev 19:17–18, the birds consuming the enemies of God).</p>",
        "46": "<p>'This day YHWH will hand you over to me... so that the whole earth may know that there is a God in Israel.' David's proclamation transforms individual combat into cosmic apologetics: the outcome will be evidence of YHWH's existence and power to all the earth. The cross similarly was not merely a judicial event but a cosmic demonstration: 'Now is the judgment of this world; now the ruler of this world will be driven out' (John 12:31). YHWH's vindication of the crucified Christ announces to the whole creation that the God of Israel is the God of all.</p>",
        "47": "<p>'The battle belongs to YHWH, and he will give all of you into our hands.' David's theological declaration is the key verse of the chapter. The battle is YHWH's before it is Israel's; the victory is accomplished at the divine level and received at the human level. This is the structure of the atonement: 'God was reconciling the world to himself in Christ' (2 Cor 5:19); the battle is God's act in Christ, with humanity as recipients rather than co-combatants. All that the believer does is claim the victory already won.</p>",
        "48": "<p>David ran quickly toward the battle line to meet Goliath — the initiative and momentum is entirely David's. The one who should be fleeing (the smaller, unarmoured shepherd) runs toward the fully-equipped giant. This is the posture of the cross: Christ 'ran' toward the confrontation, not away from it (John 18:4–5, Jesus steps forward to identify himself). The act of moving toward death rather than away from it is the movement that unmasks death's powerlessness. It only has power over those who fear it; the one who advances toward it in YHWH's name passes through it.</p>",
        "49": "<p>The stone strikes Goliath in the forehead — the one exposed point in the entire armoured figure — and sinks in. The precision of the stone's placement (a sling-stone typically travels 30–50m) is described without theological commentary; the miracle is embedded in the natural. YHWH works through David's practiced aim, not in spite of it. The stone from the brook — the humblest of weapons, taken from the ground — becomes the decisive instrument. Ps 118:22 and Dan 2:34–35, 45 use the stone as a messianic image: the rejected stone, the stone cut without hands, becomes the cornerstone and the mountain that fills the earth.</p>",
        "50": "<p>'David prevailed over the Philistine with a sling and a stone... though David had no sword in his hand.' The narrator's summary emphasises the paradox: the victory was won without the conventional weapon. Goliath's sword, spear, and javelin were useless; David's stone prevailed. Paul's meditation on divine power and human weakness (2 Cor 12:9–10) draws on this same theology: 'When I am weak, then I am strong.' The apparent weakness of the cross — a man dying without resistance — is the demonstration of the power of God (1 Cor 1:24).</p>",
        "52": "<p>Israel and Judah rise and pursue the Philistines — the people who were unable to engage the enemy for forty days now pursue them to their own cities. The victory of the representative liberates the community to act: David's combat enables Israel's campaign. Christ's victory at the cross liberates the church to advance into the world: 'You will receive power when the Holy Spirit comes upon you, and you will be my witnesses' (Acts 1:8). The champion's victory does not conclude the war but inaugurates it; the church advances in the power of the one victory already won.</p>",
        "53": "<p>The Israelites plunder the Philistine camp after the rout. The spoils of the victory belong to the victorious community — not just to the champion who won it. Christ's victory at the cross is shared with all who are in him: 'He led captivity captive and gave gifts to men' (Eph 4:8, quoting Ps 68:18). The spoils of divine victory over sin and death — righteousness, adoption, the Spirit, eternal life — are distributed to the redeemed community, not hoarded by the victor.</p>",
        "54": "<p>David takes Goliath's head to Jerusalem, where it will become a trophy of YHWH's victory. Jerusalem — the future city of God, not yet David's capital — receives the evidence of YHWH's power before the covenant people formally occupy it. The head of the enemy brought to the city of the King of kings anticipates Christ's ascension: the victorious king entering the heavenly Jerusalem after defeating the enemy, bringing the evidence of conquest (Heb 12:22; Rev 21:2). The trophy precedes the permanent establishment of the throne.</p>",
        "55": "<p>Saul's question 'whose son is this young man?' is, on one level, about genealogy and reward eligibility. On another level it is the question that the gospels answer definitively: whose son is the one who defeats the enemy? The answer David gives in v58 — 'son of your servant Jesse the Bethlehemite' — is the human genealogy. The full Christological answer is 'Son of David, Son of Abraham' (Matt 1:1) and ultimately 'Son of God' (Matt 16:16). The warrior-saviour is identified by his parentage.</p>",
        "56": "<p>'Find out whose son this young man is.' Saul's delegation of the inquiry to Abner and then the response in v58 emphasises that David's identity is established by testimony, not self-proclamation. The champion who defeats the enemy does not trumpet his own credentials; others attest to them. The Johannine testimony pattern — John the Baptist, the Father's voice, the works, the Scriptures, all testifying about Jesus (John 5:31–39) — follows the same forensic structure: the identity of YHWH's agent is established by witness, not self-assertion.</p>",
        "57": "<p>Abner brings David before Saul 'with the Philistine's head still in his hand.' The evidence of the victory is physical, present, and undeniable — held by the victor before the king who could not achieve it. Christ's resurrection appearances similarly produce physical evidence: 'Put your finger here; see my hands. Reach out your hand and put it into my side. Stop doubting and believe' (John 20:27). The risen Christ shows the wounds that are simultaneously evidence of the victory and proof of the cost at which it was won.</p>",
        "58": "<p>'I am the son of your servant Jesse the Bethlehemite.' David's self-identification — son of Jesse from Bethlehem — is the seed from which all messianic prophecy grows: Isa 11:1, the 'shoot from the stump of Jesse'; Mic 5:2, the ruler from Bethlehem; Matt 1:5–6, Jesse in the genealogy of Jesus. The champion who defeats Israel's enemy is the son of Jesse; the champion who defeats humanity's enemy is the Son of David and Son of God (Matt 22:42–45). The Bethlehemite identification is both geographic and covenantal.</p>"
    },
    "18": {
        "2": "<p>Saul keeps David at court permanently — 'did not let him return to his father's house.' The transition from Jesse's shepherd-boy to Saul's permanent courtier is the transition from private calling to public service. David enters the institutional world of the king's household, where he will be both honoured and endangered. The movement from the hidden life of the shepherd to the exposed life of the court mirrors Christ's transition from the hidden years at Nazareth to the public ministry in Jerusalem — with the same trajectory of increasing honour and increasing hostility from those in power.</p>",
        "3": "<p>Jonathan made a covenant with David because 'he loved him as his own soul.' The soul-union of Jonathan and David (<em>nĕp̄eš</em> — same word, v1 and v3) creates a covenant bond between the crown prince and YHWH's chosen king. Jonathan represents the legitimate hereditary claim to the throne voluntarily yielding to the divinely appointed successor. This is the NT pattern of John the Baptist: 'He must increase; I must decrease' (John 3:30). The rightful heir, by covenant love rather than legal process, transfers to the beloved what he could have claimed for himself.</p>",
        "5": "<p>David goes out wherever Saul sends him and succeeds in everything — 'and YHWH was with him.' The theological explanation for David's success is the same formula used for Joseph (Gen 39:2, 21, 23) and for Christ's public ministry (Acts 10:38, 'God was with him'). All of these successes are not personal merit alone but the presence of YHWH with his chosen servant. The servant's faithfulness and the divine presence are not alternatives but the same reality from two perspectives: the servant obeys, YHWH acts, and the combination produces outcomes that neither could achieve alone.</p>",
        "6": "<p>Women come out from all Israel's towns singing and dancing at David's return. The victory celebration led by women — tambourines, singing, three-stringed instruments — echoes Miriam's celebration after the Exodus (Ex 15:20–21). The women of Israel declare that YHWH has saved through a human instrument; their joyful proclamation is the liturgical response to divine deliverance. The women at the empty tomb (Matt 28:1–10; John 20:1–18) are the first to proclaim the ultimate victory, continuing this pattern of women as first voices of the resurrection-announcement.</p>",
        "7": "<p>'Saul has struck his thousands, and David his ten-thousands.' The women's song creates a comparison that is actually a praise-escalation in ANE poetic convention, not a calculation. But Saul hears it as a zero-sum comparison that diminishes him. The reaction of the established power-holder to the rising popularity of YHWH's new anointed is fear and competition rather than joy. Herod's reaction to the news of the messianic birth (Matt 2:3, 'he was troubled, and all Jerusalem with him') follows the same pattern: the arrival of the true king is perceived as a threat by those who hold power.</p>",
        "8": "<p>'What more can he get but the kingdom?' Saul correctly perceives the political trajectory: David's military success and popular acclaim are the preconditions for a transfer of power. His anger is the anger of the illegitimate occupant who recognises the true heir. Christ's opponents also identified the threat accurately: 'If we let him go on like this, everyone will believe in him, and then the Romans will come and take away both our temple and our nation' (John 11:48). The establishment's fear of Jesus was not irrational; they correctly perceived that his arrival displaced their authority.</p>",
        "9": "<p>'Saul watched David with suspicion' — the ongoing hostile surveillance of the anointed by the displaced. From this day forward, Saul's relationship with David is structured by fear and the desire to eliminate a rival. Christ's opponents similarly maintained hostile surveillance from the beginning of his ministry (Luke 6:7; Mark 3:2; John 11:57). The one who holds power illegitimately must constantly monitor the legitimate heir because the heir's very existence is a refutation. The watching is the sign of insecurity; the secure king does not surveil — he reigns.</p>",
        "10": "<p>The evil spirit from God drives Saul into frenzy the day after Goliath's defeat. The juxtaposition — greatest military triumph (v6–7) immediately followed by spiritual crisis (v10) — shows that Saul's external victories cannot address his internal condition. The evil spirit is permitted by YHWH as part of Saul's judicial abandonment; the same God who blessed David's stone is withdrawing his Spirit from the king who disobeyed. The contrast is the contrast between the Spirit upon David (16:13) and the Spirit departed from Saul (16:14) — same event from two directions.</p>",
        "11": "<p>Saul hurls the spear at David — the first of three spear-throwing episodes, the physical expression of the spiritual warfare between the displaced king and YHWH's anointed. The spear-throw fails twice; YHWH protects David. The pattern of the anointed servant preserved from the powerful person's violence recurs in the Psalms (Ps 18:17; 27:1–3) and in Christ's protected early years (Matt 2:13–14, the flight to Egypt). The powerful cannot destroy the one YHWH has appointed; their every weapon becomes impotent. 'He who is in you is greater than he who is in the world' (1 John 4:4).</p>",
        "13": "<p>Saul promotes David to commander of a thousand while removing him from his personal service — the double move of honour-and-distance. Saul simultaneously uses David's gifts and tries to remove him from influence. The strategy fails: David's campaigns increase his reputation and the people's love for him (v16). The NT parallel is the establishment's use of the early church: they cannot ignore its gifts (Acts 3:1–10; 4:13–16) but try to suppress its influence (Acts 4:17–18). YHWH's servants, promoted by YHWH, cannot be diminished by human management.</p>",
        "14": "<p>'David had success in all his undertakings, for YHWH was with him.' The twice-stated formula ('YHWH was with him' in v12 and v14) is the theological spine of the entire David narrative. Acts 10:38 applies the same formula to Christ: 'God was with him.' The servant whose success is grounded in divine presence rather than personal ambition or political support has a foundation that cannot be removed. When Saul withdraws his favour, David continues to succeed; the source of the success is not Saul. 'If God is for us, who can be against us?' (Rom 8:31).</p>",
        "15": "<p>Saul's fear of David increases with David's demonstrated competence. The king who has lost YHWH's favour cannot be protected by surrounding himself with YHWH's favoured servant; instead, the comparison becomes more painful with every success. The proximity of the anointed one to the rejected one is not comfort but condemnation. Christ's presence in the world is simultaneously salvation and judgment: 'This is the verdict: light has come into the world, but people loved darkness' (John 3:19). The proximity of the light exposes the darkness rather than merely illuminating it.</p>",
        "16": "<p>'All Israel and Judah loved David, for he led them on campaigns.' The people love what their king should be doing: leading them, going out and coming in before them (the idiom for military leadership). David is living out the function that Saul was appointed to fulfil (1 Sam 8:20) but cannot. The popular love for the rightful king prefigures the Palm Sunday entry (Matt 21:9, 'all the crowds... shouted, Hosanna to the Son of David') — the people recognising and acclaiming the one who does what the establishment cannot.</p>",
        "17": "<p>Saul offers Merab as a trap: 'only be courageous for me and fight the LORD's battles.' The rhetorical framing — 'YHWH's battles' — uses covenant language to send David into a lethal situation. The marriage offer that is actually a death-warrant deployed against the covenant servant prefigures the 'trials' of YHWH's servants throughout history. Christ himself was repeatedly offered rewards (Matt 4:8–9) and confronted with tests framed in religious language (Matt 22:15–22; Luke 20:20–26). The enemy weaponises covenant categories to create traps from within.</p>",
        "18": "<p>David's self-deprecation before Saul — 'Who am I? What is my life or my family in Israel?' — is the correct disposition of YHWH's servant before the human institution. David does not press his claim to Merab or assert his qualifications; he expresses genuine awareness of his modest social standing. The NT pattern of the truly great is consistent: John the Baptist ('I am not worthy to untie his sandals,' John 1:27), Christ's disciples ('Lord, depart from me, for I am a sinful man,' Luke 5:8). Awareness of unworthiness before the holy is the mark of the truly honoured.</p>",
        "19": "<p>Merab is given to Adriel instead of David — Saul's quiet disposal of the promised bride. The covenant promise broken by the powerful party against the weaker is the recurring motif of Saul's dealings with David. But the breach of the Merab promise becomes the occasion for Michal's love (v20) — YHWH redirects the broken promise into a different provision. The God who works all things together (Rom 8:28) can redirect human betrayal into unexpected blessing; the failed promise that destroys human plans does not derail divine purposes.</p>",
        "20": "<p>Michal loves David — the only OT statement of a woman's love as the initiating fact of a marriage. Saul learns of it and is 'pleased' — but for sinister reasons (v21). The love that Michal bears for David is real and becomes the instrument Saul intends to use for David's destruction. The world's response to Christ's beloved community similarly attempts to weaponise genuine love: the early church's love for one another was the quality that made them visible and that the persecuting authorities could use to identify members (Acts 8:3). Love makes the beloved visible and therefore vulnerable.</p>",
        "21": "<p>'She will be a trap for him — let the hand of the Philistines be against him.' Saul's plan to use Michal as a snare expresses a principle the NT makes explicit: the world is constantly attempting to use the church's attachments as leverage against Christ's body. But the plan fails structurally: David's love for Michal leads to YHWH's protection (she saves him, 19:11–12), not to his destruction. The snare becomes a rescue — the enemy's weapon reverses on the enemy. God can 'work all things together for good' (Rom 8:28) even from the enemy's planned traps.</p>",
        "22": "<p>Saul instructs his servants to speak 'privately' to David — manufactured intimacy as a deception strategy. The false encouragement ('the king is pleased with you') sets up the condition that follows. The use of genuine social goods (acceptance, belonging, honour) as bait in a deception is one of the characteristic moves of temptation throughout scripture. Christ was offered genuine goods (bread, safety, authority) in the wilderness temptation (Matt 4:1–11); the offer is real, but the source and conditions make it a trap. True provision does not come with conditions that compromise covenant faithfulness.</p>",
        "23": "<p>David's response — 'Does it seem a small thing to become the king's son-in-law? I am a poor and lightly-esteemed man' — refuses the social pressure while maintaining appropriate deference. He neither grasps at the offer nor dismisses it; he presents the honest calculation: his family cannot provide the necessary bride-price. The NT parallel is Christ's refusal to be made king by force (John 6:15) — not because kingship is inappropriate (he is king) but because that particular path to kingship is wrong. The true king receives his crown on the Father's terms, not the crowd's.</p>",
        "24": "<p>The servants report David's response to Saul. The mediation through servants continues to structure the relationship: Saul never speaks directly to David about the marriage negotiations; everything goes through intermediaries. The use of intermediaries for deception (Saul's intention) contrasts with the use of intermediaries for revelation (YHWH's prophets). Christ himself is the ultimate mediator — not because the parties distrust each other but because the distance between God and humanity required one who could bridge both (1 Tim 2:5; Heb 9:15).</p>",
        "25": "<p>The bride-price of one hundred Philistine foreskins — a military trophies requirement that Saul explicitly designs to kill David. The bride-price that requires killing enemy soldiers rather than paying money reframes the marriage as a military commission. David accepts the terms willingly. The willingness to undertake the task that is designed for the servant's destruction, and to emerge from it having completed more than required (v27: 200 foreskins), is the pattern of Christ's voluntary acceptance of the cross: 'No one takes my life from me; I lay it down of my own accord' (John 10:18).</p>",
        "26": "<p>'It pleased David to become the king's son-in-law.' David accepts the dangerous terms not because he is naive about the risk but because the goal (marriage to Michal, service to YHWH's people) outweighs the cost. The joy before him enables the endurance of the hardship: 'For the joy set before him he endured the cross' (Heb 12:2). The servant's willingness to take on a life-threatening commission for the sake of the goal it achieves is not recklessness but the calculation of love: the beloved is worth the cost.</p>",
        "27": "<p>David delivers double the required number — 200 foreskins rather than 100. The excess demonstrates not just compliance but eagerness; David does more than Saul expected or designed. The doubling of the required act is a sign of the servant's heart: 'If anyone forces you to go one mile, go with them two miles' (Matt 5:41). The grace that exceeds the requirement, the love that does more than the minimum, characterises the kingdom community. Saul is forced to honour his promise; the trap becomes the occasion for David's legitimate establishment in the royal family.</p>",
        "28": "<p>'Saul saw and knew that YHWH was with David.' The recognition of divine presence with the anointed is forced on Saul by the evidence — he cannot deny it. The same recognition is forced on those who oppose Christ: Nicodemus acknowledges 'you are a teacher from God' (John 3:2); the Pharisees cannot deny the healing of the blind man (John 9:16); even Pilate declares 'I find no basis for a charge against him' (John 18:38). The truth of the anointed one forces itself onto the consciousness of those who would suppress it.</p>",
        "29": "<p>'Saul was David's enemy all his days.' The permanent enmity of the displaced king toward YHWH's chosen is the sustained context of the rest of the Samuel narrative. Saul's enmity is not resolved by David's continued service, loyalty, or gifts; it intensifies. The structural enmity of the world toward Christ and his body (John 15:18–19) is similarly permanent within the current age: 'All who desire to live a godly life in Christ Jesus will be persecuted' (2 Tim 3:12). The enmity is not personal but structural — the world system cannot coexist peacefully with YHWH's anointed.</p>",
        "30": "<p>'David performed more successfully than all Saul's servants, and his name was highly honoured.' The chapter that began with Israel's paralysis before Goliath ends with David's name honoured throughout Israel. The arc from obscurity (Jesse's youngest son sent on an errand) to honour (name held in highest regard by all Israel) is the humiliation-to-exaltation pattern of Phil 2:6–11: 'Therefore God exalted him to the highest place and gave him the name that is above every name.' The servant who humbles himself receives the name that is honoured; the one who exalts himself will be humbled (Luke 14:11).</p>"
    }
}

